The Accord's three-party structure established the pattern of distributed authority that Midgaard's governance layers have preserved even as the original parties dissolved into modern institutions.
The River Factors became the grain merchant guild structure; the Upland Syndicate became the northern trade registry; the Temple Compact became the tribunal arbitration system, now housed in the public courts rather than temple premises.
The Lantern Reforms' standardization of paving marks, posted tariffs, and night patrol routes were the first formal elaboration of the Accord's "watched square" principle into a legible city-wide system.
Continuity faction doctrine treats the Accord as the constitutional source from which all legitimate charter law derives; any governance question can in principle be resolved by tracing it back to which Accord obligation it addresses.
Reckoning faction critique holds that the Accord's founding parties all held legitimate grievances against each other that the tribunal mechanism suppressed rather than resolved — making the Accord's public-tribunal principle simultaneously foundational and selectively applied from the beginning.
The Accord's text is displayed in the public tribunal chambers; the Reckoning faction notes that the display version omits the militia contribution clause's original language, which specified reciprocal protection obligations that were not honored during the Ash-and-Iron years for external populations.
The Charter Sovereignty office's authority to refuse annexation petitions derives from the Accord's founding premise: sovereignty of the converging routes was the reason the compact was formed, and sovereignty remains the compact's highest value.

