The Neon Covenant was written with full awareness of the First Stone Accord's structure and deliberately diverged from it on the question of founding parties.
The Accord had three founding groups; the Covenant had six founding houses — a deliberate expansion of the power-sharing base to prevent any single two-party coalition from dominating.
The Accord's "public tribunal rather than private violence" principle was preserved in the Covenant's "one square, final judgment" clause, but Kowloon's version added the physical covenant stone as a grounding object — a material anchor for institutional memory that Midgaard's Accord lacked.
Kowloon's Jade Magistracy reads the First Stone Accord as evidence that institutional design is path-dependent: Midgaard's current governance complexity traces to the simplicity of the Accord's founding moment, and that simplicity created structural gaps that had to be patched with additional layers.
The Neon Covenant was written to close those gaps from the beginning, which is why Kowloon's governance is more complex at founding but has required fewer emergency amendments.
Kowloon considers the First Stone Accord a legitimate founding instrument but not a transferable model — Midgaard's geographic position and Kowloon's delta position created different founding problems requiring different founding solutions.

