Kiess's founding charter explicitly cites the First Stone Accord as the origin point of the governance tradition it both inherits and critiques.
The citation is precise: Kiess's anti-sealed-warrant clause states that it supplements the Accord's public-tribunal principle by specifying that no party to a tribunal proceeding may be stripped of civic identity through registry reclassification before their case is heard.
This supplement addresses the specific failure mode that occurred during the Ash-and-Iron years: the Violet Compact processed tribunal defendants as "arcane material" before proceedings were complete, eliminating their standing to contest the outcome.
Kiess's three-power governance structure (Syndic Council, Warden Circle, Covenant Bench) mirrors the Accord's three founding parties but with formal mutual-censure mechanisms that the original Accord lacked.
The obsidian disc bearing the Spirebound Conclave's seal is kept by the Syndic Council alongside a copy of the First Stone Accord text — a physical pairing that asserts the institutional continuity between the Accord's founding and the Conclave's exploitation of the governance systems it generated.
Kiess's legal scholars consider the Accord the most important document in the five-city network's institutional history because it established the framework within which all subsequent failures occurred.

