---
Human governance doctrine in Midgaard treats the First Stone Accord as the foundational text from which all legitimate authority derives.
The three founding parties were human-majority institutions operating human trade networks; the Accord was designed for and by humans managing human commerce through dangerous terrain.
The governance tradition the Accord established has no explicit framework for non-human founding parties, non-human civic participants, or non-human knowledge systems.
This absence is the structural source of every classification failure in Midgaard's subsequent history: when non-human populations arrived in quantity — Ashborn displaced by the Ashfall, Khephari corridor communities absorbed by route expansion, Deltari refugees from the delta settlements — the intake system had no founding-document basis for treating them as civic actors rather than managed populations.
Human policy analysts in Midgaard's Continuity faction argue that the Accord's founding was appropriate to its historical moment and that subsequent amendments have addressed its gaps.
Human policy analysts in the Reckoning faction argue that amendments layered on a founding document that excluded non-human civic standing produce systems that formally include non-humans while structurally treating them as exceptions.
The debate is unresolved. The Accord's text is unchanged.
